{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490963"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:25:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:25:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"787"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/787"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.16,0.05,0.02,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"787"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62594"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/787"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"787"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48041"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1158"},{"type":"tags","id":"2043"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1484"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2741"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45056"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62594"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents with a three week history of intermittent spontaneous bleeding from her right nipple. Her last menstrual period was two weeks ago. There is no significant medical history. She has not had any previous breast problems and is not on any medications. She has three children, the youngest being 14. She had a tubal ligation after this child\u0027s birth. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure is 110/60mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 97% on air, and temperature 37.0C. She appears well. Both breasts appear normal, with no palpable masses. On gentle palpation in the 2 o\u0027clock position, a small amount of blood can be expressed from a single duct on the right nipple. The left breast is normal and no blood can be expressed from the nipple.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intraductal papilloma","Ductal carcinoma in situ","Periductal mastitis","Fibrocystic disease","Paget\u0027s disease"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENipple discharge can be caused by\u00a0ductal ectasia, intraductal papilloma, or rarely breast cancer. Isolated spontaneous bloody nipple discharge coming from a single duct should point towards a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eintraductal papilloma\u003C/strong\u003E. This is supported in the stem by the fact the discharge occurs on palpation of a particular area (duct) of the breast. Duct ectasia is caused by multiple ducts releasing green/yellow discharge, generally only on manipulation of the nipple.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuctal carcinoma in situ\u003C/strong\u003E (DCIS) is more commonly discovered in asymptomatic woman during routine screening. Occasionally it may present as a breast lump or with bloody nipple discharge. Although intraductal papillomas are a much more common cause of bloody nipple discharge, DCIS needs to be excluded.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeriductal mastitis\u003C/strong\u003E is due to inflammation or infection of the ducts within the breast. Smoking is a major risk factor for the condition. It is likely to present as painful, swollen and erythematous breast, that may have some abnormal nipple discharge. This stem does not suggest the breast is tender or inflamed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrocystic breast disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign condition that usually presents with pain and many small lumps/cysts within the breasts, not nipple discharge.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPaget\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a change to nipple appearance rather than discharge, such as ulceration, crusting or inversion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Isolated bloody nipple discharge should point towards a diagnosis of intraductal papilloma.","DCIS needs to be excluded as a cause of bloody nipple discharge with appropriate imaging and pathology.","Duct ectasia can present as green/yellow nipple discharge."],"references":["Li A, Kirk L. Intraductal Papilloma. [Updated 2020 Dec 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2020 Jan-. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519539/","Cancer Australia Contributors, 2020. Breast Cancer. Australian Government. Available at: https://www.canceraustralia.gov.au/affected-cancer/cancer-types/breast-cancer/ductal-carcinoma-situ.","Zhang Y, Zhou Y, Mao F, Guan J, Sun Q. Clinical characteristics, classification and surgical treatment of periductal mastitis. J Thorac Dis. 2018;10(4):2420-2427. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29850148/","Malherbe K, Fatima S. Fibrocystic Breast Disease. [Updated 2020 Jul 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2020 Jan-. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551609/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48041"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"787"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48041"},"attrib